content.description: Variation to Little Dihedral. At the top of the dihedral, move right to the roof and over lichen covered rock to the top.

This is the first prominent wide crack as you come down the west face from the Railing Routes. A face variation starts fifteen feet left, between the flakes and joins the crack above. Near the top of the crack, follow a ledge right and move over the bulge on good holds. Easy face leads to the top. Doing it in two pitches may ease rope drag.

climbs.name: Sierra Club RCS Railing Route Right

content.description: The right of two climbs just below the railing at the top.  Steep, but with positive hands to give the relatively low rating.
content.protection: Aliens are very helpful.  Nothing above #3 camalot.  #.5-3 camalots cam be used for an anchor.

climbs.name: Sierra Club RCS Railing route Left

content.description: The left of two climbs just below the railing at the top of the peak.  Follow a thin crack up to the top.  head left toward the top for the 5.9 route.  Head right for a stiffer variation.
content.protection: Aliens are very helpful.  Nothing above #2 camalot.  #.5-3 camalots cam be used for an anchor.

content.description: Fifty feet downhill from the railing routes, climb a right facing stepped dihedral. Follow the face above, up a seam to the top.
content.protection: Poor protection suggests either a diaper or a top rope.

content.description: Begin climbing in a tree at the base of the face around the corner from the Green Dihedral, taking any of several variations up to a prominent thin crack, then up to a belay.
A lieback and face route near the center of the separate large block, below the railing routes.

Obvious line on the right side of the steep gully. Make full use of the ledges and cracks on either side, not staying strictly in the crack. Belay at the second tree on the gully's left side. A harder, enjoyable variation tot he right eliminates the tight chimney.

climbs.name: Peace in Mississippi
climbs.fa: Bob VanBelle, Mike Paul, Doug White

content.description: Nice face climb left of the Green Dihedral. Begin at the right end of the face, pass two bolts to a sloping ledge, traverse left 15 feet, then pst two more bolts to the top.
content.protection:
Wired nuts, draws, a long sling for second bolt.

If the bolts have not been replaced, they'll need it.
content.location: Right side of the upper tier

content.description: 15 feet up the Left Chimney, move left onto an aesthetic open book, making an exposed move around left at the top. Continue up and establish a belay.
A large, steep gully separates the upper tier, with a large white face to the right. The Left Chimney takes the fissure on the left side of this gully.

On the right side of the upper tier is an obvious dihedral with a steep thin section exiting to he left. Above the thin section one may go up the crack, traverse left , or go just left and over the roof, in order of increasing difficulty. Exiting right before the thin section makes the route much easier.
content.location: Right side of the upper tier, walk down.

content.description: 20 feet right of the Stonewall Squeeze is a large crack system starting from an alcove. Move up the left crack systems to a bolt and pin belay used on the first ascent. Continue up passing one bolt and over the roof on thin holds, belaying at the top of the Little Dihedral. No reason why this route can't be done in one pitch.
content.protection:
standard rack

If bolts haven't been replaced, they should be.

content.description: Just left of the Left Chimney, face climb to the large roof and hand traverse up the left edge. Face climb to a crack, climb this and continue up to easier ground.
